"Decharme B., Douville H.","Global validation of the ISBA sub-grid hydrology",2007,"Climate Dynamics","29","1",,"21","37",,,10.1007/s00382-006-0216-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34248595621&partnerID=40&md5=49f70fdad631a671b25fe1a22eb15be5","CETP-IPSL-CNRS, 10 avenue de l'Europe, Velizy-Villacoublay 78140, France; Météo-France, CNRM/GMGEC/UDC, 42 Avenue G. Coriolis, Toulouse 31057, France","Decharme, B., CETP-IPSL-CNRS, 10 avenue de l'Europe, Velizy-Villacoublay 78140, France; Douville, H., Météo-France, CNRM/GMGEC/UDC, 42 Avenue G. Coriolis, Toulouse 31057, France","Over recent years, many numerical studies have suggested that the land surface hydrology contributes to atmospheric variability and predictability on a wide range of scales. Conversely, land surface models (LSMs) have been also used to study the hydrological impacts of seasonal climate anomalies and of global warming. Validating these models at the global scale is therefore a crucial task, which requires off-line simulations driven by realistic atmospheric fluxes to avoid the systematic biases commonly found in the atmospheric models. The present study is aimed at validating a new land surface hydrology within the ISBA LSM. Global simulations are conducted at a 1° by 1° horizontal resolution using 3-hourly atmospheric forcings provided by the Global Soil Wetness Project. Compared to the original scheme, the new hydrology includes a comprehensive and consistent set of sub-grid parametrizations in order to account for spatial heterogeneities of topography, vegetation, and precipitation within each grid cell. The simulated runoff is converted into river discharge using the total runoff integrating pathways (TRIP) river routing model (RRM), and compared with available monthly observations at 80 gauging stations distributed over the world's largest river basins. The simulated discharges are also compared with parallel global simulations from five alternative LSMs. Globally, the new sub-grid hydrology performs better than the original ISBA scheme. Nevertheless, the improvement is not so clear in the high-latitude river basins (i.e. Ob, MacKenzie), which can be explained by a too late snow melt in the ISBA model. Over specific basins (i.e. Parana, Niger), the quality of the simulated discharge is also limited by the TRIP RRM, which does not account for the occurrence of seasonal floodplains and for their significant impact on the basin-scale water budget. © Springer-Verlag 2007.",,"climate change; climate forcing; floodplain; global warming; hydrological response; river basin; river discharge; runoff; snowmelt; water budget; Australasia; Mackenzie Basin; New Zealand; South Island",,,,,,"Alsdorf, D.E., Lettenmaier, D.P., Tracking fresh water from space (2003) Science, 301, pp. 1485-1488; Arora, V.K., Boer, G.J., A variable velocity flow routing algorithm for GCMs (1999) J Geophys Res, 104, pp. 30965-30979; Beljaars, A.C.M., Viterbo, P., Miller, M.J., The anomalous rainfall over the United States during July 1993: Sensitivity to land surface parametrization and soil moisture anomalies (1996) Mon Weather Rev, 124, pp. 739-805; Beven, K.J., Kirkby, M.J., A physically-based variable contributing area model of basin hydrology (1979) Hydrol Sci Bull, 24, pp. 43-69; Boone, A., Etchevers, P., An intercomparison of three snow scheme of varying complexity coupled to the same land surface model: Local-scale evaluation at an alpine site (2001) J Hydrometeorol, 2, pp. 374-394; Boone, A., Calvet, J.C., Noilhan, J., Inclusion of a third soil layer in a land surface scheme using the force-restore method (1999) J Appl Meteorol, 38, pp. 1611-1630; Boone, A., Masson, V., Meyers, T., Noilhan, J., The influence of the inclusion of soil freezing on simulation by a soil-atmosphere-transfer scheme (2000) J Appl Meteorol, 9, pp. 1544-1569; Boone, A., The Rhône-aggregation land surface scheme intercomparison project: An overview (2004) J Clim, 17, pp. 187-208; Chapelon, N.,